Ac- cordingly the writer speaks first of the games which were first celebrated at the Megalesia, and then he speaks of other games (scenic) celebrated at the ,Megalesia also.

The story of Scipio Africanus and the Ludi is in Livy (34. c. 54): “Horum aedilium ludos Romanos primus senatus a populo secretus spectavit—Postremum ipsum quoque Africanum, quod consul auctor ejus rei fuisset poenituisse ferunt.'⁷ Here the story is told of the Ludi Romani.
